  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Developments\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the United States\n- First international anti-money laundering guidelines\n- Initial focus on reporting large cash transactions\n\n2. Key International Milestones\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established in 1989\n- Creation of comprehensive international standards\n- Recommendations for global cooperation\n\n3. Major Legislative Expansions\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Stricter customer due diligence regulations\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Regulations addressing digital currencies\n- Expanded monitoring of online financial transactions\n- Enhanced cybersecurity requirements\n\n5. Recent Trends\n- Increased transparency requirements\n- Beneficial ownership disclosure mandates\n- More sophisticated transaction monitoring\n- Cryptocurrency and blockchain-specific regulations\n\n6. Global Compliance\n- Standardized international reporting frameworks\n- Cross-border information sharing\n- Coordinated enforcement mechanisms\n\n7. Ongoing Challenges\n- Emerging financial technologies\n- Complex transnational financial networks\n- Continuous adaptation of regulatory frameworks\n\nThe legislation continues to evolve in response to changing financial landscapes and emerging criminal techniques.",
